# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1984-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1804.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party's ticket of incumbent president Thomas Jefferson and former New York governor George Clinton defeated the Federalist Party's ticket of former U.S. minister to France Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and former U.S. minister to the United Kingdom Rufus King.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election held under the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which required separate ballots for president and vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was unanimously renominated by his party's congressional nominating caucus in February; the caucus selected Clinton to succeed the outgoing vice president, Aaron Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] A "semisecret" Federalist caucus elevated Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates; while news of the caucus was widely circulated, in states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists in several states chose not to nominate electors, resulting in a lopsided popular vote margin for Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was widely popular and considered unbeatable by many observers, following his narrow election four years earlier.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Economic prosperity, the expansion of voting rights, and the disorganized state of the opposition all benefited his campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists portrayed Jefferson as a demagogue for his embrace of populist, democratic politics, and a dictator for his use of patronage and reforms to the federal judiciary.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's complicity in slavery did little to damage his candidacy even in New England, where he carried the Federalist stronghold of Massachusetts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two electoral districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received the electoral votes of Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were appointed by the legislature, and two votes from unpledged electors in Maryland.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson polled more than 106,000 popular votes, representing 73 percent of the total, compared with fewer than 40,000 votes for the Federalist electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Federalist president John Adams sought re-election in 1800, but was defeated by Democratic-Republican challenger Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's running mate, Aaron Burr, was elected vice president following a contingent election in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The right to vote was widespread in the United States during the Early Republic, including the large majority of adult white men.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The expansion of voting rights during Jefferson's first term included the establishment of universal white male suffrage in Maryland in 1801.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Propertied, single women retained the right to vote in New Jersey, while Black men who met all other property and taxpaying requirements were eligible in New England, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most places, voting was by secret ballot.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] (Kentucky and Virginia retained the English custom of oral voting.) Eligible individuals voted using paper tickets, typically handwritten, listing the voter's choice for the various offices.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Enforcement of property and taxpaying qualifications was generally lax, in part due to the frequency of land sales, which outpaced officials' ability to keep accurate records of ownership.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In other cases, local opinion or the threat of rioting might compel election officials to permit veterans and small landholders to vote when otherwise disenfranchised by state law.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congress passed the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which was ratified by the states prior to the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Amendment instructed the United States Electoral College to elect the president and vice president on separate ballots.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists opposed ratifying the Amendment, hoping to exploit the original electoral system to sow discord in the Democratic-Republican ranks.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign, some Federalists encouraged the Democratic-Republican electors from New York to support Clinton for president over Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Efforts to delay ratification of the Amendment were unsuccessful, and the new system took effect in September 1804 in time for the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson faced no internal opposition to his bid for re-election; the Democratic-Republican congressional caucus nominated him unanimously on February 25.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] With Burr out of the running, the selection of the vice-presidential candidate was the caucus's main responsibility.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] George Clinton and John Breckinridge were the leading contenders for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton had served as governor of New York for most of the last thirty years and was a veteran of the American Revolutionary War; he had received 50 electoral votes in the 1792 United States presidential election, and declined a place on the Democratic-Republican ticket in 1800.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although of advanced age, his political views aligned with Jefferson's, and he remained popular with Democratic-Republicans in his home state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge, a Kentuckian, was the choice of Western Democratic-Republicans concerned with regional representation.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other candidates included the U.S. attorney general, Levi Lincoln Sr.; the former U.S. senator from New Hampshire, John Langdon; and the U.S. postmaster general, Gideon Granger.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas McKean was discussed as a possible contender, but withdrew prior to the caucus.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 110 Democratic-Republican members of Congress.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton won the nomination with 67 votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Federalists did not meet formally to nominate a ticket, as they had done in the previous election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party was ill-prepared to mount a national campaign, and few believed Jefferson could be defeated.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, a "semisecret caucus" in Washington proposed Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates on February 22.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although this meeting was widely reported, significant uncertainty persisted concerning the identities of the Federalist candidates throughout the campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist electors remained formally unpledged.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans established a vast network of state, county, town, and ward committees to conduct the campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states such as Ohio, the overriding importance of the presidential election was an agent of party unity.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republicans organized celebrations to commemorate the anniversary of Jefferson's first inauguration on March 4 and the Louisiana Purchase on May 11.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Parades, dinners, and toasting were the mainstays of such events.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Supporters sang campaign songs such as "Jefferson and Liberty," written to commemorate the last election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican militia units, professional associations, benevolent societies, and partisan groups like the Young Men of Democratic Principles were visible supporters of the president's re-election campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans made effective use of the partisan press.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party's national paper, the *National Intelligencer*, was widely circulated and supported a vast array of state and local print publications.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican campaign catered to the nation's developing white male democracy.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The abandonment of property requirements for voting in Maryland and New Jersey benefited Jefferson, whose economic policies were considered favorable to working people.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican newspapers and broadsides were written in plain language accessible to the average person.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The themes of "simplicity and frugality" and equality of opportunity were central to the party's appeal to voters, contrasted against Federalist elitism.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast to the Democratic-Republicans, the Federalists entered the campaign demoralized and to some degree leaderless.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney displayed little interest in the election and devoted most of 1804 to a local campaign against dueling.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party lost its most influential leader in July, when Alexander Hamilton was killed in a duel by the outgoing vice president, Burr.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's former deputy, Timothy Pickering, saw no hope for the presidential election and instead advocated for New England to secede from the United States.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other Federalists simply withdrew from politics rather than endure a seemingly inevitable defeat.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard, advocated for the party to update its tactics.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The growth of mass politics in the early nineteenth century made the Federalists' reliance on elite relationships increasingly obsolete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists held celebrations on the anniversary of Washington's birthday and organized groups like the Washington Benevolent Societies.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The effectiveness of the party press was hindered by the stilted, formal style of many Federalist newspapers.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of Jefferson, rather than enthusiasm for Pinckney, characterized the Federalist campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the party nominated electors, its ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist press generally avoided mention of Pinckney and King; the Boston *Columbian Centinel* denied that the Federalist electors were pledged to Pinckney.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Dauer argues that the uncertainty surrounding the Federalist ticket cost the party the electoral votes of Massachusetts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists described Jefferson as an aspiring dictator.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] They compared the Louisiana Purchase to Napoleon's European conquests and accused Jefferson of violating the Constitution, which did not specify the president's power to acquire new territory.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Increasingly, Federalists saw parallels between Jefferson's administration and the rule of European tyrants, including Napoleon, Maximilien Robespierre, and Julius Caesar.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's use of patronage and the impeachment of Samuel Chase by the House of Representatives in March 1804 were criticized by Federalists who feared Jefferson's growing influence over the political system.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The repeal of the Midnight Judges Act and the reduction of the United States Armed Forces were cast as attempts to dismantle the federal government of the United States.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's sexual relationship with Sally Hemings, an enslaved woman and the half-sister of his late wife, Martha Jefferson, was first exposed by James T.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had six children with Hemings between 1795 and 1808, although some historians argue their relationship began much earlier, during Jefferson's tenure as the U.S. minister to France.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists seized on the scandal to attack Jefferson's hypocrisy and personal character.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Partisan journals printed doggerel mocking Jefferson's promiscuity with verses that emphasized Hemings's race and complexion.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In pillorying Jefferson as an enslaver, Federalist writers did not intend to critique social inequality; instead, they sought to use Jefferson's complicity in slavery to discredit democratic politics.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists attacked Jefferson's religious views, which they described as atheism.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist ministers characterized the Democratic-Republican Party as a grave threat to Christianity.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's economic policies catered to the interests of free men and entrepreneurs, in contrast to Federalist policies that prioritized wealthy creditors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Joyce Appleby argues that Jefferson's laissez-faire posture facilitated commercial expansion that benefited white men regardless of class.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Whereas the Federalists used economic regulation to promote the interests of creditors, Democratic-Republicans favored a decentralized economy in which opportunities to participate in commerce were more broadly accessible.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists interpreted Democratic-Republican policies as an attack on elite privilege and defended the principle of economic inequality.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although many Democratic-Republicans were skeptical of national corporations, corporations and banks flourished at the state and local level.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both Jefferson and Pinckney were enslavers.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney played a critical role in the adoption of the Three-Fifths Clause by the Constitutional Convention and opposed the efforts to end the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson criticized slavery in print, but did little either privately or politically to diminish it; as president, he withheld diplomatic recognition from the First Empire of Haiti, the first independent state in the Americas established as the result of a successful slave rebellion.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attempted to make slavery an issue in New England, with limited success.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both national parties sought to avoid discussion of slavery during the 1790s; after 1801, the decline of the Federalist Party in the Southern United States freed Northern Federalists to attack slavery more directly.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Antislavery rhetoric featured in some Federalists' critiques of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists demanded the repeal of the Three-Fifths Clause, which disadvantaged the region in terms of congressional apportionment.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] These appeals largely failed to motivate opposition to Jefferson, while accompanying calls for secession met with little popular support.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of the Three-Fifths Clause emphasized New England Federalists' partisan self-interest.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Many Federalists blamed this provision for their defeat in the last election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Fisher Ames wrote that "black votes" had elected Jefferson in 1800 and that the administration therefore lacked a popular mandate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists frequently pointed to prominent Democratic-Republicans' complicity in slavery as evidence of the party's hypocrisy.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Opposing political rights for both white and Black workers, they pointed to the contradictions in Jeffersonian democracy as proof that a political system based on mass participation was unworkable.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists appeared to win the popular vote on Election Day in North Carolina's Fayetteville district, but the exclusion of the return from Montgomery County, North Carolina, subsequently gave the district's single electoral vote to Jefferson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson carried Massachusetts and New Hampshire, as well as seven of nine Maryland districts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, Jefferson carried every county except Adams, where a last-minute Federalist effort narrowly succeeded in keeping the county out of the Democratic-Republican column.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Ohio Federalists' attempt to split the Democratic-Republican Party was unsuccessful, and the Jefferson electors defeated the Federalist ticket by a wide margin.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists did not contest the remaining popular vote states, but unpledged electors received write-in votes in New Jersey and Virginia.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received electoral votes from Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were chosen by the state legislature, while Jefferson swept the remaining states for a total of 162 electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Jefferson was the first of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, Cleveland, Roosevelt, and Trump were also their respective party's nominees for three consecutive elections.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Nineteenth-century election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential nominee, if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table compares the votes for the most popular elector on each ticket.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In the single-member districts in Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee, the result is the sum of all votes for electors pledged to one nominee.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, where several distinct anti-Jefferson tickets ran in different parts of the state, the result shown is the sum of the votes for the leading electors in each county.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1808.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican candidate James Madison defeated Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney decisively.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Madison had served as Secretary of State since President Thomas Jefferson took office in 1801.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, who had declined to run for a third term, threw his strong support behind Madison, a fellow Virginian.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Sitting Vice President George Clinton and former Ambassador James Monroe both challenged Madison for leadership of the party, but Madison won his party's nomination and Clinton was renominated as vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists chose to re-nominate Pinckney, a former ambassador who had served as the party's 1804 nominee, again alongside Rufus King.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the unpopularity of the Embargo Act of 1807, Madison won the vast majority of electoral votes outside of the Federalist stronghold of New England.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton received six electoral votes for president from his home state of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first of two instances in American history in which a new president was selected but the incumbent vice president won re-election, the other being in 1828.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley, who had chaired the congressional nominating caucus during the 1804 presidential election, made a call for the 1808 caucus to the 146 Democratic-Republican members of the United States Congress and Federalist allies.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 89 to 94 members of Congress.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] With the support of outgoing President Thomas Jefferson, Secretary of State James Madison won the presidential nomination over opposing candidates James Monroe and Vice President George Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus voted to give the vice presidential nomination to Clinton over his main opponent John Langdon, although Clinton's supporters believed Clinton would receive the Federalist Party's presidential nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists instead nominated Charles Cotesworth Pinckney that September.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] A committee of fifteen members was selected to manage Madison's campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Seventeen Democratic-Republicans in Congress opposed Madison's selection and the caucus system whose authority to select presidential and vice-presidential candidates was disputed.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe, who was supported by dissident and majority leader John Randolph, was nominated by a group of Virginia Democratic-Republicans (Old Republicans), and although he did not actively try to defeat Madison, he also refused to withdraw from the race.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was also supported by a group of New York Democratic-Republicans for president even as he remained the party's official vice presidential candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist caucus met in September 1808 and re-nominated the party's 1804 ticket, which consisted of General Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina and former Senator Rufus King of New York.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only time in American history that a defeated major party renominated its losing ticket for a second time.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The election was marked by opposition to Jefferson's Embargo Act of 1807, a halt to trade with Europe that disproportionately hurt New England merchants and was perceived as favoring France over Britain.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, Jefferson was still very popular with Americans generally and Pinckney was soundly defeated by Madison, though not as badly as in 1804.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received few electoral votes outside of New England.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney retained the electoral votes of the two states that he carried in 1804 (Connecticut and Delaware), and he also picked up New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and three electoral districts in North Carolina besides the two electoral districts in Maryland that he carried earlier.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Except for the North Carolina districts, all of the improvement was in New England.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe won a portion of the popular vote in Virginia and North Carolina, while the New York legislature split its electoral votes between Madison and Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The popular vote totals used are the elector from each party with the highest total of votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The vote totals of Kentucky, North Carolina, and Tennessee appear to be incomplete.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 30 to December 2, 1812.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In the shadow of the War of 1812, incumbent Democratic-Republican President James Madison narrowly defeated DeWitt Clinton, the lieutenant governor of New York and mayor of New York City, who drew support from dissident Democratic-Republicans in the North as well as Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first presidential election to be held during a major war involving the United States.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] As no significant British incursions into American territory had occurred by that time, and Britain's war strategy was largely defensive, the election proceeded without disruption.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Democratic-Republicans had long been dissatisfied by the Southern dominance of their party, and DeWitt Clinton's uncle, Vice President George Clinton, had unsuccessfully challenged Madison for the party's 1808 presidential nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] While the May 1812 Democratic-Republican congressional nominating caucus re-nominated Madison, the party's New York caucus, also held in May, nominated Clinton for president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] After the United States declared war on the United Kingdom in June 1812, Clinton sought to create a coalition of anti-war Democratic-Republicans and Federalists.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] With Clinton in the race, the Federalist Party declined to formally put forth a nominee, hoping its members would vote for Clinton, but they did not formally endorse him, fearing that an explicit endorsement of Clinton would hurt the party's fortunes in other races.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist Jared Ingersoll of Pennsylvania became Clinton's de facto running mate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] A dissident faction of the Federalist Party attempted to nominate former vice presidential candidate Rufus King over Clinton, but only succeeded in doing so in Virginia.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Despite Clinton's success at attracting Federalist support, Madison was re-elected with 50.4 percent of the popular vote to his opponent's 47.6%, making the 1812 election the closest election up to that point in the popular vote (there was no popular vote in half the states).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton won the Federalist bastion of New England as well as three Mid-Atlantic states, but Madison dominated the South and took Pennsylvania.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] This was the narrowest popular vote margin for a victorious re-elected president until 2004.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The British provided additional provocations by impressing American seamen, maintaining forts within United States territory in the Northwest, and supporting Native Americans at war with the United States in both the Northwest and Southwest.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, expansionists in the south and west of the United States coveted British Canada and Spanish Florida and wanted to use British provocations as a pretext to seize both areas.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The pressure steadily built, with the result that the United States declared war on the United Kingdom on June 12, 1812.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] This occurred after Madison had been nominated by the Democratic-Republicans, but before the Federalists had made their nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans in the northern states were unhappy over the perceived dominance of the presidency by the state of Virginia (three of the last four presidents had been Virginians), and they wished instead to nominate one of their own rather than re-nominate President Madison.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, these hopes were pinned upon Vice President George Clinton, but his poor health and advanced age of 72 eliminated his chances.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Even before Clinton's death on April 20, 1812, his nephew New York Lieutenant Governor DeWitt Clinton was considered the preferred candidate to move against Madison by the northern Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Hoping to forestall a serious movement against President James Madison and a division of the Democratic-Republican Party, some proposed making DeWitt Clinton the nominee for the vice presidency, taking over the same office his uncle now held.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] DeWitt Clinton was not opposed to the offer, but preferred to wait until after the conclusion of the New York caucus, which would not be held until after the congressional caucus had met, to finalize his decision.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Early caucuses were held in the states of Virginia and Pennsylvania, both of which pledged their support to Madison.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Eighty-three of the one hundred thirty-eight of the Democratic-Republican members of the United States Congress attended the nominating caucus in May 1812.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The delegations from New York and New England had less representation due to the New York members supporting DeWitt Clinton's attempt to gain the support of the Federalists and the New England members opposing Madison's foreign policy.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Eighty-two of the delegates voted to give the presidential nomination to Madison while John Langdon won the vice-presidential nomination against Elbridge Gerry by a vote of sixty-four to sixteen.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] However, Langdon declined the nomination citing his age and it was instead given to Gerry after another vote was held with seventy-four delegates voting for him.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] When the New York caucus did meet on May 29, it was dominated by anti-war Democratic-Republicans, and nominated DeWitt Clinton for the presidency almost unanimously.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton's now open candidacy was opposed by many who, while not friends of James Madison, feared that Clinton was now apt to tear the Democratic-Republican party asunder.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The matter of how to conduct his campaign also became a major problem for Clinton, especially with regards to the war with the British after June 12.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Many of Clinton's supporters were war-hawks who advocated extreme measures to force the British into negotiations favorable to the United States, while Clinton knew he would have to appeal to Federalists to win, and they were almost wholly opposed to the war.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Before Clinton entered the race as an alternative to President Madison, Chief Justice John Marshall was a favorite for the Federalist presidential nomination, a relatively popular figure who could carry much of the Northeast while potentially taking Virginia and North Carolina as well.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] But with Clinton in the race, the Federalists would no longer be able to count on the electoral votes of New York, possibly throwing the election into the House of Representatives, dominated by Democratic-Republicans, where Madison would almost certainly be elected.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In the face of these facts, the Federalist party considered endorsing Clinton's candidacy for a time, but at their caucus in September it was decided that the party simply would not field a presidential candidate that year and did not endorse Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] A Federalist caucus in Pennsylvania chose to nominate Jared Ingersoll, the Attorney General of the state, as Clinton's vice presidential running-mate, a move Clinton decided to support considering the importance of Pennsylvania's electors.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] While many Federalists were supportive of DeWitt Clinton's candidacy, others were not so keen, skeptical of Clinton's positions regarding the war and other matters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Rufus King, a former diplomat and Representative, had led an effort at the September Caucus to nominate a Federalist ticket for the election that year, though he was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Still, some wished to enter King's name into the race under the Federalist label, and while very little came of it, it caused problems for the Clinton campaign in two states.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In the case of Virginia, Clinton was rejected entirely by the state Federalist Party, which instead chose to nominate Rufus King for president and William Richardson Davie for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The ticket would acquire about 27% of the vote in the state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, with the Federalists having gained control of the state legislature that summer, it was planned that the Federalists would nominate a slate pledged to Rufus King now that they had the majority.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] However, a coalition of Democratic-Republicans and Federalists would defeat the motion and succeed in nominating a slate pledged to Clinton.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The war heavily overshadowed the campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton continued his regional campaigning, adopting an anti-war stance in the Northeast (which was most harmed by the war), and a pro-war stance in the South and West.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The election ultimately hinged on New York and Pennsylvania, and while Clinton took his home state, he failed to take Pennsylvania and thus lost the election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Though Clinton lost, the election was the best showing for the Federalists since that of Adams, as the party made gains in Congress and kept the presidential election reasonably close.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Clintonite Democratic-Republicans in many states refused to work with their Federalist counterparts (notably in Pennsylvania) and Clinton was generally regarded by most as the Federalist candidate, though he was not formally nominated by them.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was the first of just four presidents in United States history to win re-election with a lower percentage of the electoral vote than in their prior elections, as Madison won 69.3% of the electoral vote in 1808, but only won 58.7% of the electoral vote in 1812.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The other three were Woodrow Wilson in 1916, Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt in 1940 and 1944 and Barack Obama in 2012.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, Madison was the first of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections, although in 1812, only 6 of the 18 states chose electors by popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The other four are Andrew Jackson in 1832, Grover Cleveland in 1892, Franklin Roosevelt in 1940 and 1944, and Barack Obama in 2012.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] This was the closest re-election for an incumbent president until the 2004 election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] James Madison was 5 ft 4 in (163 cm), and DeWitt Clinton stood 6 ft 0 in (183 cm).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In no other US presidential election has the height difference between candidates (8 inches or 20 cm) been so great where the winner was the shorter candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Madison electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Madison would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Returns below are from A New Nation Votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] The vote totals of Kentucky appear to be incomplete, and those of Tennessee appear to be lost.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In New Jersey, Federalists had just taken over the state legislature and decided to change the method of choosing electors from a general election to appointment by state legislature.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] Some towns, possibly too far away to get the news, or in open defiance of the switch, held elections anyway.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] These were not counted nor reported by the newspapers.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1812-united-states-presidential-election] In the unofficial elections, Madison received 1,672 votes while Clinton only received 2, suggesting these were protest votes (New Jersey was far more competitive than this at the time).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 1984.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Republican president Ronald Reagan and his running mate, incumbent vice president George H.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They defeated the Democratic ticket of former vice president Walter Mondale and New York congresswoman Geraldine Ferraro in a landslide.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan and Bush faced only token opposition in their bid for re-nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale faced a competitive field in his bid, defeating Colorado senator Gary Hart, activist Jesse Jackson, and several other candidates in the Democratic primaries.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He eventually chose New York representative Geraldine Ferraro as his running mate, the first woman to be on a major party's presidential ticket.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan touted a strong economic recovery from the 1970s stagflation and the 1981–1982 recession, and the widespread perception that his presidency had overseen a revival of national confidence and prestige.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At 73, Reagan was the oldest person to be nominated by a major party for president, a record that stood until 2020, when both major-party candidates were older.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Reagan campaign produced effective television advertising and deftly neutralized concerns regarding Reagan's age.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale criticized Reagan's supply-side economics and budget deficits.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He called for the reduction of U.S. public debt, a nuclear freeze, and ratification of the Equal Rights Amendment.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan won re-election carrying 525 electoral votes, 49 states, and 58.8% of the popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale won 13 electoral votes: 10 from his home state of Minnesota, which he won by a narrow margin of 0.18% (3,761 votes), and 3 from the District of Columbia, which has always voted overwhelmingly for the Democratic candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan won the second-largest share of the Electoral College since 1820 (second only to Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roosevelt in 1936 and the largest for a Republican), and the most raw electoral votes ever received by a candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As of 2026, Reagan is the last Republican to sweep all of New England and the only presidential nominee to win all the New England and Southern states since the effectively uncontested election of 1820.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the most recent election in which any candidate won the popular vote by double digits and more than 500 electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is also the most recent election in which a major party candidate failed to win at least 100 electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the time, Reagan received the most popular votes in history, a record stood until it was broken by both major party candidates in 2004.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ronald Reagan entered the presidency with an unemployment rate of 7.3% and it peaked at 10.6% in December 1982.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States had a negative gross domestic product growth in 1982.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republicans performed poorly in the 1982 elections.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kennedy, Richard Nixon, and Jimmy Carter lost an average of 12 seats in the United States House of Representatives in their first midterm.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republicans lost 26 seats in the House elections.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republicans lost seven governorships as well.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan's approval rating fell to 35% by January 1983.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polling showed him losing to Democratic candidates, including Walter Mondale and John Glenn; however, unemployment fell to 7.7% by March 1984, and Reagan's approval rating was at 54% in January 1984.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His approval rating was aided by the 1983 Beirut barracks bombings and the invasion of Grenada.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polling by *CBS News* and *The New York Times* in January 1984 showed him leading Mondale by 16%.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan-Bush '84, under the leadership of Ed Rollins, was organized on October 17, 1983.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan delayed his campaign announcement as not running would make him a lame duck whereas running would make everything he did be viewed as part of his campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He announced that he would seek re-election on January 29, 1984.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senate Majority Leader Howard Baker were considered as possible candidates only if Reagan did not run.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former Minnesota governor Harold Stassen opposed Reagan for the Republican nomination and criticized the President's foreign policy, the budget deficit, and the trade imbalance.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan was the first incumbent president since Richard Nixon in 1972 to face no significant opposition for renomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan was renominated by a vote of 2,233 delegates (two delegates abstained).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the only time in American history, the vice presidential roll call was taken concurrently with the presidential roll call.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last time in the 20th century that the vice-presidential candidate of either major party was nominated by roll call vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Only three Democratic candidates won any state primaries: Mondale, Hart, and Jackson.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Initially, Massachusetts Senator Ted Kennedy, after a failed bid to win the 1980 Democratic nomination for president, was considered the *de facto* front-runner of the 1984 primary.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Kennedy announced in December 1982 that he did not intend to run.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former Vice President Mondale was then viewed as the favorite to win the Democratic nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale had the largest number of party leaders supporting him, and he had raised more money than any other candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, both Jackson and Hart emerged as surprising, and troublesome, opponents.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] South Carolina Senator Ernest Hollings's wit, experience, and call for a budget freeze all won him some positive attention, but his relatively conservative record alienated liberal Democrats, and he was never really noticed in a field dominated by Mondale, John Glenn, and Gary Hart.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hollings dropped out two days after losing badly in New Hampshire and endorsed Hart a week later.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His disdain for his competitors was at times showcased in his comments.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] California Senator Alan Cranston hoped to galvanize supporters of the nuclear freeze movement that had called on the United States to halt the deployment of existing nuclear weapons and the development of new ones.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Glenn and Askew hoped to capture the support of moderate and conservative Democrats.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] None of them shared Mondale's fundraising prowess nor Hart's or Jackson's grassroots support, however, and none won any contests.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Jackson was the second African-American (after Shirley Chisholm) to mount a nationwide campaign for the presidency, and he was the first black candidate to contend seriously.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He got 3.5 million votes during the primaries, third behind Hart and Mondale.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He won the primaries in Virginia, South Carolina, and Louisiana, and split Mississippi, where there were two separate contests for Democratic delegates.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Through the primaries, Jackson helped confirm the black electorate's importance to the Democratic Party in the South at the time.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, however, Jackson made an off-the-cuff reference to Jews as "Hymies" and New York City as "Hymietown", for which he later apologized.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, the remark was widely publicized, and derailed his campaign for the nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Jackson ended up winning 21% of the national primary vote but received only 8% of the delegates to the national convention, and he initially charged that his campaign was hurt by the same party rules that allowed Mondale to win.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also poured scorn on Mondale, saying that Hubert Humphrey was the "last significant politician out of the St.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart, from Colorado, was a more serious threat to Mondale, and after winning several early primaries it looked as if he might take the nomination away from Mondale.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart finished a surprising second in the Iowa caucuses, with 16.5% of the vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This established him as the main rival to Mondale, effectively eliminating John Glenn, Ernest Hollings and Alan Cranston as alternatives.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart criticized Mondale as an "old-fashioned" Great Society Democrat who symbolized "failed policies" of the past.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart positioned himself (just as Bill Clinton would eight years later) as a younger, fresher, and more moderate Democrat who could appeal to younger voters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He emerged as a formidable candidate, winning the key New Hampshire, Ohio, and California primaries as well as several others, especially in the West.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Hart could not overcome Mondale's financial and organizational advantages, especially among labor union leaders in the Midwest and industrial Northeast.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart was also badly hurt in a televised debate with Mondale during the primaries, when the former vice president used a popular television commercial slogan to ridicule Hart's vague "New Ideas" platform.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Turning to Hart on camera, Mondale told Hart that whenever he heard Hart talk about his "New Ideas", he was reminded of the Wendy's fast-food slogan "Where's the beef?" The remark drew loud laughter and applause from the viewing audience and caught Hart off-guard.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Hart never fully recovered from Mondale's charge that his "New Ideas" were shallow and lacking in specifics.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At a roundtable debate between the three remaining Democratic candidates moderated by Phil Donahue, Mondale and Hart got into such a heated argument over the issue of U.S. policy in Central America that Jackson had to tap his water glass on the table to help get them to stop.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, at the Democratic National Convention in San Francisco on July 16, Mondale received the overwhelming support of the unelected superdelegates from the party establishment to win the nomination.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale's nomination marked the second time since the nomination of former governor of Georgia Jimmy Carter in 1976, and the fourth time since the nomination of former Representative John W.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Davis in 1924, that the Democratic Party nominated a private citizen for president (i.e., someone not serving in an official governmental role at the time of the nomination and election).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale was the last private citizen to be nominated for president by the Democratic Party until former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton in 2016.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was also the last former vice president to be nominated for president until Joe Biden in 2020.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This race for the Democratic Party presidential nomination was the closest in two generations, and, as of 2024, it was the last occasion that a major party's race for the presidential nomination went all the way to its convention.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] When he made his acceptance speech at the Democratic Convention, Mondale said: "Let's tell the truth.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] I just did." Although Mondale intended to expose Reagan as hypocritical and position himself as the honest candidate, the choice of raising taxes as a discussion point likely damaged his electoral chances.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale wanted to establish a highly visible precedent with his vice presidential candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ferraro from New York as his running mate, making her the first woman nominated for that position by a major party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another reason for the nominee to "go for broke" instead of balancing the ticket was Reagan's lead in the polls.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale hoped to appeal to women, who were the majority of voters by 1980.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition to her sex, Mondale chose Ferraro because he hoped she would attract ethnic voters with her personal background.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Unsuccessful nomination candidate Jesse Jackson derided Mondale's vice-presidential screening process as a "P.R. parade of personalities", but praised Mondale for his choice, having himself pledged to name a woman to the ticket in the event he was nominated.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale had wanted to choose New York Governor Mario Cuomo as his running mate, but Cuomo declined and recommended Ferraro, his protégée.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale might have named Massachusetts Governor Michael Dukakis as his running mate had he wanted to make a "safe" choice", while others preferred Senator Lloyd Bentsen because he would appeal to more conservative Southern voters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The National Unity Party was an outgrowth of John B.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anderson's presidential campaign from 1980.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anderson hoped that the party would be able to challenge the "two old parties", which he viewed as being tied to various special interest groups and incapable of responsible fiscal reform.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The intention was to organize the new party in California, Oregon, Washington, Illinois, the New England states, and others where his previous candidacy had proven to have experienced the most success.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party was also eligible for $5.8 million in Federal election funds, but its qualification depended on it being on the ballot in at least ten states; however, it remained unclear if National Unity or Anderson personally was eligible to obtain the funds.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At first, Anderson opposed running, hoping that another notable politico would take the party into the 1984 election, and feared that his own candidacy might result in the party being labeled a "personality cult".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, no candidate came forward, resulting in Anderson becoming the nominee in waiting.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In light of this, in addition to difficulties in getting on the ballot in his targeted states (Utah and Kentucky were the only two, neither among those he intended to prominently campaign in), Anderson ultimately declined to run.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anderson announced that he would not run on April 26, 1984.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He later endorsed Mondale and a survey of National Unity members showed that they supported his action.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anderson had hoped that the party would continue to grow and field candidates in 1986, and later a presidential candidate in 1988.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Burns was the initial frontrunner for the nomination, but withdrew, citing concerns that the party would not be able to properly finance a campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The remaining candidates were Bergland; Ravenal, who had worked in the Department of Defense under Robert McNamara and Clark Clifford; and Ruwart.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bergland narrowly won the presidential nomination over Ravenal.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ticket appeared on 39 state ballots.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Sonia Johnson ran in the 1984 presidential election, as the presidential candidate of the Citizens Party, Pennsylvania's Consumer Party and California's Peace and Freedom Party.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Johnson received 72,161 votes (0.1%) finishing fifth.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Her running mate for the Citizens Party was Richard Walton and for the Peace and Freedom Party Emma Wong Mar.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One of her campaign managers, Mark Dunlea, later wrote a novel about a first female president, *Madame President*.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Communist Party USA ran Gus Hall for president and Angela Davis for vice president.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following graph depicts the standing of each candidate in the poll aggregators from July 1983 to Election Day.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale unsuccessfully tried to replace Charles Manatt with Bert Lance as chair of the DNC.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale made Lance the chair of his presidential campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Lance had to be removed due to controversy over his tenure as director of the Office of Management and Budget.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan's lead in polling declined after the Republican convention due to its strong right-wing stances.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan was also criticized for a joke about bombing the Soviet Union.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, polls showed that voters believed Mondale was "too cautious and vague" and was trying to appeal to too many special interest groups.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Roger Stone and other strategists working for Reagan viewed Ohio, where unemployment was 10%, as his most vulnerable state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan made appeals to Evangelical voters during the campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He declared January 22, 1984, to be National Sanctity of Human Life Day.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The American Coalition for Traditional Values (ACTV), under the leadership of Tim LaHaye, was tasked with maintaining Evangelical support.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ACTV planned on registering 2.5 million voters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] LaHaye sent a letter to 45,000 ministers in sixteen states, under the title of the Christian Voter Program, asking for them to support Reagan's campaign and register voters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mondale ran a liberal campaign, supporting a nuclear freeze and the Equal Rights Amendment (ERA).
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He spoke against what he considered to be unfairness in Reagan's economic policies and the need to reduce federal budget deficits.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While Ferraro's choice was popular among Democratic activists, polls immediately after the announcement showed that only 22% of women were pleased about her selection, versus 18% who believed that it was a bad idea.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] 60% of all voters thought that pressure from women's groups had led to Mondale's decision, versus 22% who believed that he had chosen the best available candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some members of the hierarchy of the Roman Catholic Church criticized the Catholic Ferraro for being pro-choice on abortion.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Already fighting an uphill battle with voters, Ferraro also faced a slew of allegations, mid-campaign, directed toward her husband, John Zaccaro.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These allegations included Zaccaro's possible past involvement in organized crime, pornography distribution, and campaign contribution violations.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ferraro responded to these allegations against her husband by releasing her family tax returns to the media on August 21, 1984.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, the damage to the campaign was already done.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At a campaign stop in Hammonton, New Jersey, Reagan said, "America's future rests in a thousand dreams inside your hearts.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Two of the more memorable Reagan campaign ads were commonly known as "Morning in America" and, after the difficult first debate for the president, "Bear in the woods".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Reagan was the oldest president to have served to that time (at 73) and there were questions about his capacity to endure the grueling demands of the presidency, particularly after Reagan had a poor showing in the first 1984 United States presidential debates with Mondale on October 7.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He referred to having started going to church "here in Washington", although the debate was in Louisville, Kentucky, referred to military uniforms as "wardrobe", and admitted to being "confused", among other mistakes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the next debate on October 21, however, in response to a question from journalist Henry Trewhitt about his age, Reagan joked, "I will not make age an issue of this campaign.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were two presidential debates and one vice presidential debate during the 1984 general election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1960 that the voter turnout percentage rose relative to its predecessor.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan was re-elected in the November 6 election in an electoral and popular vote landslide, winning 49 states by the time the ballots were finished counting on election night at 11:34 PM in Iowa.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He won a record 525 electoral votes total (of 538 possible), and received 58.8% of the popular vote; despite Ferraro's selection, 55% of women who voted did so for Reagan, and his 54 to 61% of the Catholic vote was the highest for a Republican candidate in history.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Mondale's 13 electoral college votes marked the lowest total of any major presidential candidate since Alf Landon's 1936 loss to Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt, and the fewest of any Democrat since Stephen A.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Douglas claimed 12 in the 1860 election, as well as the worst for a Democrat in a two-way race.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Davis, and George McGovern did worse in the popular vote.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the second-largest share of the Electoral College any president won since 1820, when James Monroe won a near unanimous electoral victory, and the most raw electoral votes received by a candidate.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the last time any candidate won the popular vote by double digits.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] When Reagan was asked in December 1984 what he wanted for Christmas he joked, "Well, Minnesota would have been nice".
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan became the first Republican to ever win two terms in the White House without carrying Minnesota at least once, a feat later duplicated by George W.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was the most recent in which the Republican candidate won every state in the Northeastern, Southern, and Pacific regions of the United States, and won at least one county in every state.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt's 1,876 total electoral votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan's landslide victory resulted in him winning 97.6% of electoral votes, behind only Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, Reagan's popular vote share was below those of elected presidents Warren G.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson in 1964, and Richard Nixon in 1972.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His margin of victory was also lower than those for elected presidents Theodore Roosevelt in 1904, Harding in 1920, Calvin Coolidge in 1924, Franklin D.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan's percentage in each state rose from 1980, with his best performances occurring in the South and states with high third-party votes.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Mondale improved upon Carter's 1980 results in 28 states, but performed worse in 22 states, 15 of which were in the South.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Mondale's share of the popular vote was 0.4 percentage points lower than Carter's.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Republicans gained seats in the concurrent U.S.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] House of Representatives elections and lost two seats in the concurrent U.S.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Senate elections, but overall control of both chambers remained the same.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan underperformed Republican senatorial candidates in Alaska, Colorado, Kansas, Maine, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, South Carolina, South Dakota, Virginia, and Wyoming.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Jesse Helms of North Carolina and Mitch McConnell of Kentucky were the only Republican senatorial candidates who could have benefited from the coattails effect.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Psephologists attributed a factor of the Republican victory to "Reagan Democrats", millions of Democrats who voted for Reagan, as in 1980.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Democratic National Committee commissioned a study after the election that came to these conclusions, but destroyed all copies of the final report, afraid that it would offend the party's key voters.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The percentage of Democrats who voted for Reagan ranged from 16 to 26% while Republicans voting for Mondale ranged from 3 to 7% according to exit polls by the *Los Angeles Times*, NBC, ABC/*The Washington Post*, and CBS News/*The New York Times*.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] One-third of people who supported Hart during the Democratic primary voted for Reagan.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Polling by CBS News and *The New York Times* reported that 66% of Anderson voters supported Mondale while 27% supported Reagan and 61% of Carter voters supported Mondale while 25% supported Reagan.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Twenty-two percent of those who did not vote in 1980 supported Reagan while 18% supported Mondale.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Reagan, who won 63% of white evangelical voters in 1980, received 80% of their votes against Mondale.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2024, this marked the last election where the Republican nominee won Hawaii, Massachusetts, New York, Oregon, Rhode Island, and Washington.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the last time that the tipping point state (in this case, Michigan) was decided by a double-digit margin.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At age 73, Reagan was the oldest president ever to win a presidential election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Thirty-six years later, in 2020, Joe Biden surpassed this record at age 77, as did Donald Trump in 2024 at age 78.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] However, Reagan remains the oldest incumbent president to win a presidential election.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Maine allowed its electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:1984-united-states-presidential-election/1984-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote to the winner of each congressional district.
